00:31:18.720 --> 00:31:22.060
And now, if you combine--
if you multiply--

00:31:22.060 --> 00:31:29.860
the gradient of the electric
field with the dipole moment,

00:31:29.860 --> 00:31:30.940
and average.

00:31:30.940 --> 00:31:33.250
The cosine part goes
with the cosine part,

00:31:33.250 --> 00:31:35.220
the sine part goes
with the sine part,

00:31:35.220 --> 00:31:38.910
and the cos terms average out.

00:31:38.910 --> 00:31:42.130
So therefore, we have
the simple result

00:31:42.130 --> 00:31:46.710
that we have two
contributions to the [? old ?]

00:31:46.710 --> 00:31:49.530
mechanical force of light.

00:31:49.530 --> 00:31:55.280
And the u component--
the in phase component--

00:31:55.280 --> 00:32:00.110
of the dipole moment goes with
the amplitude of the gradient.

00:32:00.110 --> 00:32:02.910
And the in quadrature
component goes

00:32:02.910 --> 00:32:05.900
with the gradient of the phase.

00:32:05.900 --> 00:32:09.100
So in other words, when
it comes to light forces,

00:32:09.100 --> 00:32:12.640
the cosine component
and the sine component

00:32:12.640 --> 00:32:15.160
of the dipole moment
talk, actually,

00:32:15.160 --> 00:32:18.590
to two different
quantities associated

00:32:18.590 --> 00:32:21.280
with the electromagnetic field.

00:32:21.280 --> 00:32:25.860
It's just in phase
and in quadrature.

00:32:25.860 --> 00:32:26.430
OK.

00:32:26.430 --> 00:32:36.920
Now I just have to tell you
a few definitions and names.

00:32:36.920 --> 00:32:40.640
This component, which goes
with the in phase component,

00:32:40.640 --> 00:32:43.160
is called the reactive force.

00:32:43.160 --> 00:32:49.060
Whereas the other one is
called the dissipative force.

00:32:49.060 --> 00:32:52.010
The name, of course, comes
that if you have a harmonic

00:32:52.010 --> 00:32:56.860
oscillator, the component
which oscillates in quadrature

00:32:56.860 --> 00:33:01.050
absorbs directly energy,
whereas the in phase component

00:33:01.050 --> 00:33:04.480
does not absorb energy.

00:33:04.480 --> 00:33:06.500
I'll leave it for
a little bit later

00:33:06.500 --> 00:33:10.770
in our discussion how you
can have a force and not

00:33:10.770 --> 00:33:12.370
exchange energy.

00:33:12.370 --> 00:33:14.140
That's a little
bit a mystery when

00:33:14.140 --> 00:33:17.130
we talk about cooling
with a reactive force.

00:33:17.130 --> 00:33:21.520
We will have to scrutinize
what happens with energy,

00:33:21.520 --> 00:33:24.350
because at least
in the most basic,

00:33:24.350 --> 00:33:28.580
the in phase component
of the oscillating system

00:33:28.580 --> 00:33:32.750
does not extract energy from
the electromagnetic field.

00:33:32.750 --> 00:33:35.060
So maybe just
believe that for now,

00:33:35.060 --> 00:33:40.190
and we will scrutinize it later.

00:33:40.190 --> 00:33:42.980
Any questions?

00:33:42.980 --> 00:33:43.850
Am I going too fast?

00:33:47.950 --> 00:33:48.960
Am I going too slow?

00:33:53.100 --> 00:33:55.230
Does it mean about right?

00:33:55.230 --> 00:33:55.730
OK.

00:33:59.730 --> 00:34:05.180
So we have now obtained the
reactive force, which is also

00:34:05.180 --> 00:34:07.550
called the dipole force
or stimulated force,

00:34:07.550 --> 00:34:10.000
and the dissipated
force, which is also

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:11.840
called the spontaneous force.

00:34:14.820 --> 00:34:19.190
The next thing is
purely nomenclature.

00:34:19.190 --> 00:34:23.510
We want to introduce
appropriate vectors

00:34:23.510 --> 00:34:26.559
which point along the
gradient of the phase,

00:34:26.559 --> 00:34:31.909
and which point along the
gradient of the amplitude.

00:34:31.909 --> 00:34:34.570
And this is done here.

00:34:34.570 --> 00:34:36.659
So we want to say
that the reactive

00:34:36.659 --> 00:34:39.800
and the dissipative
force are written

00:34:39.800 --> 00:34:44.852
in a very sort of similar
way, but the one off them

00:34:44.852 --> 00:34:47.409
points in the direction
of a vector, alpha,

00:34:47.409 --> 00:34:51.110
the other one in the
direction of a vector, beta.

00:34:51.110 --> 00:34:55.730
The beta vector is the
gradient of the phase.

00:34:55.730 --> 00:34:59.660
If the phase is kr, the
gradient of the phase

00:34:59.660 --> 00:35:03.200
is simply k, the k vector
of the electromagnetic wave.

00:35:03.200 --> 00:35:06.130
So that will come in handy
in just a few seconds.

00:35:06.130 --> 00:35:10.510
Whereas the reactive
force points

00:35:10.510 --> 00:35:15.160
into the direction of the
gradient of the amplitude,

00:35:15.160 --> 00:35:18.220
but we never want to talk
about electromagnetic field

00:35:18.220 --> 00:35:18.720
amplitude.

00:35:18.720 --> 00:35:23.760
For us, we always use the
electric field in terms of you

00:35:23.760 --> 00:35:25.590
parametrize the Rabi frequency.

00:35:25.590 --> 00:35:28.190
The Rabi frequency is
really the atomic unit

00:35:28.190 --> 00:35:29.710
of the electric field.

00:35:29.710 --> 00:35:32.470
So therefore, this
vector which involves now

00:35:32.470 --> 00:35:36.810
the gradient of the amplitude,
becomes a normalized gradient

00:35:36.810 --> 00:35:40.100
of the Rabi frequency.

00:35:40.100 --> 00:35:44.557
So these are the two fundamental
light forces, the reactive

00:35:44.557 --> 00:35:45.640
and the dissipative force.

00:35:53.190 --> 00:35:55.320
OK.

00:35:55.320 --> 00:35:59.710
Now we are going to have a
quick look at those two forces.

00:35:59.710 --> 00:36:03.370
So therefore, I'm now
discussing the two

00:36:03.370 --> 00:36:06.740
simple, but already
very characteristic

00:36:06.740 --> 00:36:08.650
cases for those forces.

00:36:08.650 --> 00:36:14.090
One is we want to look at
a plane travelling wave,

00:36:14.090 --> 00:36:18.190
and then we want to look
at a pure standing wave.

00:36:18.190 --> 00:36:22.090
And the beauty of it is in
a plane travelling wave,

00:36:22.090 --> 00:36:25.690
you've a plain wave, the
amplitude of the electric field

00:36:25.690 --> 00:36:29.120
is constant everywhere,
it just oscillates.

00:36:29.120 --> 00:36:33.380
And therefore, this
alpha vector is zero.

00:36:33.380 --> 00:36:36.710
And in a few minutes, we
look at this standing wave,

00:36:36.710 --> 00:36:39.830
and in the standing wave,
the beta vector is zero.

00:36:39.830 --> 00:36:44.660
So the travelling wave and the
standing wave allows us now

00:36:44.660 --> 00:36:49.080
to look at the two forces
separately in two physical

00:36:49.080 --> 00:36:53.110
situations which are--
as you will see later--

00:36:53.110 --> 00:36:56.276
highly relevant for experiments.

00:36:56.276 --> 00:37:00.376
Well, I don't think I have to
tell anybody in this room--

00:37:00.376 --> 00:37:01.750
maybe except some
people who take

00:37:01.750 --> 00:37:03.640
the course for
[? Brett's ?] requirement--

00:37:03.640 --> 00:37:06.620
that standing waves
or optical lattices

00:37:06.620 --> 00:37:08.260
are common in all labs.

00:37:08.260 --> 00:37:10.960
And similar,
traveling wave beams

00:37:10.960 --> 00:37:15.100
are used, for instance, for
decelerating atomic beams.

00:37:15.100 --> 00:37:17.270
So we illustrate
the two forces now,

00:37:17.270 --> 00:37:21.615
but we already discussing two
experimentally very important

00:37:21.615 --> 00:37:22.115
geometries.

00:37:27.010 --> 00:37:29.850
OK, plain travelling waves.

00:37:29.850 --> 00:37:34.860
I mean, I just really plug
now the electromagnetic field

00:37:34.860 --> 00:37:37.930
for plain travelling wave,
I plug it into the equations

00:37:37.930 --> 00:37:39.700
above.

00:37:39.700 --> 00:37:42.090
The important thing is--
and which simplifies things

00:37:42.090 --> 00:37:45.390
a lot-- is that the
alpha vector is zero.

00:37:45.390 --> 00:37:47.420
The amplitude of
the plain wave is--

00:37:47.420 --> 00:37:49.810
that's what a plain
wave is-- constant.

00:37:49.810 --> 00:37:54.040
And the beta vector is the
gradient of the Rabi frequency

00:37:54.040 --> 00:37:58.630
is just the k
vector of the light.

00:37:58.630 --> 00:38:04.030
So therefore, the dissipative
or spontaneous light force

00:38:04.030 --> 00:38:10.680
was the Rabi frequency times
the v component of the Optical

00:38:10.680 --> 00:38:15.340
Bloch vector times h bar k.

00:38:15.340 --> 00:38:21.800
And this has a very
simple interpretation

00:38:21.800 --> 00:38:24.590
because the steady state
solution of the Optical Bloch

00:38:24.590 --> 00:38:28.100
Equation is nothing else than
gamma times the excited state

00:38:28.100 --> 00:38:29.770
population.

00:38:29.770 --> 00:38:35.420
And since the excited state
scatters, or emits photons

00:38:35.420 --> 00:38:38.880
at a rate, gamma,
this is nothing else

00:38:38.880 --> 00:38:43.020
than the number of
absorbed emitted

00:38:43.020 --> 00:38:47.680
scattered photons times h bar k.

00:38:47.680 --> 00:38:50.470
We are in steady state
here, so the number

00:38:50.470 --> 00:38:54.840
of photons which are emitted
into all space, into the vacuum

00:38:54.840 --> 00:38:57.450
has to be the number
of photons which

00:38:57.450 --> 00:39:00.870
has been absorbed
into the laser beam.

00:39:00.870 --> 00:39:04.010
So therefore, the interpretation
here is very simple,

00:39:04.010 --> 00:39:05.410
you have a laser beam.

00:39:05.410 --> 00:39:09.150
Every time the atom
absorbs a photon, it

00:39:09.150 --> 00:39:13.360
receives a recoil
transfer, h bar k.

00:39:13.360 --> 00:39:16.910
Now, afterwards, the
photon is scattered,

00:39:16.910 --> 00:39:20.710
but the scattering is
symmetric, and does not

00:39:20.710 --> 00:39:23.350
impart the force onto the atom.

00:39:23.350 --> 00:39:25.320
And this is what we
discussed earlier.

00:39:25.320 --> 00:39:27.820
The quantum part of the
electromagnetic field

00:39:27.820 --> 00:39:29.090
is symmetric.

00:39:29.090 --> 00:39:32.450
And here, we see sort of
what it means visually.

00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:35.140
Spontaneous emission
goes equally

00:39:35.140 --> 00:39:39.770
probable in opposite direction,
and there is no net force,

00:39:39.770 --> 00:39:41.720
but there is heating
as we discussed later.

00:39:45.080 --> 00:39:54.120
So we can plug in the solution--
the steady state solution--

00:39:54.120 --> 00:39:56.200
from the Optical Bloch Equation.

00:39:56.200 --> 00:39:58.540
That's our Lorentzian.

00:39:58.540 --> 00:40:00.710
We have discussed power
broadening already

00:40:00.710 --> 00:40:03.710
when we discussed the
Optical Bloch Equation.

00:40:03.710 --> 00:40:07.260
And, of course,
I just remind you

00:40:07.260 --> 00:40:11.830
if you saturate the system with
a strong laser power, what you

00:40:11.830 --> 00:40:14.630
can obtain is that
half of the population

00:40:14.630 --> 00:40:17.115
is in the excited state,
and half of the population

00:40:17.115 --> 00:40:18.880
is in the ground state.

00:40:18.880 --> 00:40:24.290
Under those circumstances,
do you get the maximum force.

00:40:24.290 --> 00:40:26.440
And the maximum
spontaneous force

00:40:26.440 --> 00:40:31.080
is the momentum per photon
times the maximum rate at which

00:40:31.080 --> 00:40:33.070
a two-level atom
can scatter photons.

00:40:36.820 --> 00:40:39.100
So that's, in a
nutshell, I think

00:40:39.100 --> 00:40:42.960
all you have to know about
the spontaneous light force

00:40:42.960 --> 00:40:46.600
as far as the
force is concerned.

00:40:46.600 --> 00:40:50.640
But we still have to discuss
the heating associated

00:40:50.640 --> 00:40:53.225
with a spontaneous force, which
are the force fluctuations.

00:40:55.617 --> 00:40:56.116
Questions?

00:41:01.780 --> 00:41:07.280
Well, then let's do
a similar discussion

00:41:07.280 --> 00:41:09.015
with reactive forces.

00:41:12.390 --> 00:41:20.260
Which is a little bit richer
because, well, you will see.

00:41:20.260 --> 00:41:23.380
So a standing wave
is parametrized here.

00:41:30.260 --> 00:41:32.880
We only have an alpha
vector, not a beta vector

00:41:32.880 --> 00:41:36.220
now, because
everything is in phase,

00:41:36.220 --> 00:41:39.990
there is no phase phi of r.

00:41:39.990 --> 00:41:45.630
So therefore, there is
no dissipative force,

00:41:45.630 --> 00:41:47.730
the only force is
a reactive force.

00:41:50.260 --> 00:41:54.160
Since the reactive
force depends only on u,

00:41:54.160 --> 00:41:58.200
there is no exchange of energy.

00:41:58.200 --> 00:42:04.870
So that raises the question,
what is really going on it is

00:42:04.870 --> 00:42:08.970
only the reactive part with
u, how can the atom really--

00:42:08.970 --> 00:42:13.480
How can the motion change if
it cannot exchange energy?

00:42:13.480 --> 00:42:17.070
Well, we'll come to that
in different pieces.

00:42:17.070 --> 00:42:20.080
The one part I want to
sort of discuss here

00:42:20.080 --> 00:42:25.772
is that you should--
I want to show you

00:42:25.772 --> 00:42:27.455
that at the level
of our discussion

00:42:27.455 --> 00:42:31.000
we can already understand
that the atom is actually

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:35.700
doing a redistribution
of energy and momentum.

00:42:35.700 --> 00:42:39.030
Well, if I only hold
onto my standing wave,

00:42:39.030 --> 00:42:42.520
there is no energy exchange
because the atom is always

00:42:42.520 --> 00:42:44.580
in phase with the
standing wave--

00:42:44.580 --> 00:42:48.880
the atomic dipole-- which is
this one [INAUDIBLE] force.

00:42:48.880 --> 00:42:54.580
But I can now do what
everybody does in the lab.

00:42:54.580 --> 00:42:58.022
We generate the standing wave
as a superposition of two

00:42:58.022 --> 00:42:58.730
travelling waves.

00:43:03.210 --> 00:43:08.600
And if I have a superposition
of two traveling waves,

00:43:08.600 --> 00:43:12.560
there is a point in space where
the phases of the traveling

00:43:12.560 --> 00:43:14.150
waves are the same.

00:43:14.150 --> 00:43:16.450
Then one phase is
advanced in phase,

00:43:16.450 --> 00:43:20.390
and the other side one of the
waves is lagging in phase.

00:43:20.390 --> 00:43:25.300
And for pedagogical reasons,
I pick the point where the two

00:43:25.300 --> 00:43:29.110
travelling waves are 90
degree phase shifted.

00:43:34.860 --> 00:43:36.480
OK.

00:43:36.480 --> 00:43:45.550
Now the situation is that
we have our electric field

00:43:45.550 --> 00:43:50.330
and what is responsible for the
reactive light force is the u

00:43:50.330 --> 00:43:53.780
part of the dipole moment of
the Optical Bloch vector, which

00:43:53.780 --> 00:43:56.370
oscillates in phase.

00:43:56.370 --> 00:44:00.900
But nobody prevents me from
analyzing it with respect

00:44:00.900 --> 00:44:03.310
to E1 and E2.

00:44:03.310 --> 00:44:06.780
And so if I ask now, I
say, I have one laser beam.

00:44:06.780 --> 00:44:08.000
I have another laser beam.

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:11.140
And if you want, after the
laser beams have crossed,

00:44:11.140 --> 00:44:14.260
you can put in two photo-diodes,
and you can not only

00:44:14.260 --> 00:44:15.855
ask, what happens
to the standing

00:44:15.855 --> 00:44:20.165
wave, you can also ask, what
happens to each traveling wave?

00:44:20.165 --> 00:44:21.040
Are photons absorbed?

00:44:21.040 --> 00:44:23.110
Or what happens?

00:44:23.110 --> 00:44:28.040
And now, what is obvious
is if you have an harmonic

00:44:28.040 --> 00:44:31.360
oscillator, and you have an
oscillating dipole moment,

00:44:31.360 --> 00:44:35.180
if the dipole moment
is withing 0 and 180

00:44:35.180 --> 00:44:39.650
degrees with a dry
field, you absorb power.

00:44:39.650 --> 00:44:44.840
If it is in the two
other quadrants,

00:44:44.840 --> 00:44:47.390
it emits, or delivers power.

00:44:47.390 --> 00:44:50.610
And now you see, that
we are in a situation--

00:44:50.610 --> 00:44:56.100
which I've peak here-- where one
travelling wave loses energy,

00:44:56.100 --> 00:44:59.900
and the other traveling
wave gains energy.

00:44:59.900 --> 00:45:01.590
And there is a
classic experiment,

00:45:01.590 --> 00:45:04.880
which was done by Bill Phillips
a while ago-- he had atoms

00:45:04.880 --> 00:45:09.190
in an optical lattice,
and they were sloshing.

00:45:09.190 --> 00:45:13.410
And she could really measure
that when the atoms were

00:45:13.410 --> 00:45:18.500
accelerated this way, one of
the laser beams gained power,

00:45:18.500 --> 00:45:20.260
and the other one lost power.

00:45:20.260 --> 00:45:22.310
So while the atoms
where sloshing

00:45:22.310 --> 00:45:26.850
in momentum space, the power
between the two laser beams

00:45:26.850 --> 00:45:29.660
was distributed back and forth.

00:45:29.660 --> 00:45:32.650
So this is the character
of the dissipative force,

00:45:32.650 --> 00:45:38.080
that it redistributes momentum
and energy between the two

00:45:38.080 --> 00:45:38.890
traveling waves.

00:45:48.422 --> 00:45:49.005
Any questions?

00:45:54.590 --> 00:45:55.090
Boris?

00:45:55.090 --> 00:45:56.631
AUDIENCE: But if
there's a net change

00:45:56.631 --> 00:45:58.823
in the patterns of
motion, the energy still

00:45:58.823 --> 00:46:00.066
has to come from somewhere.

00:46:00.066 --> 00:46:01.557
Right?

00:46:01.557 --> 00:46:03.048
Can you make that [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:16.979 --> 00:46:18.520
PROFESSOR: This
question has bothered

00:46:18.520 --> 00:46:21.010
in many different iterations.

00:46:21.010 --> 00:46:25.310
And at some point, I found a
very, very easy answer to it.

00:46:25.310 --> 00:46:27.830
And this is one of your
homework assignments

00:46:27.830 --> 00:46:29.410
for homework number 10.

00:46:29.410 --> 00:46:31.360
There's a very
simple example where

00:46:31.360 --> 00:46:33.380
you will realize where
the energy comes.

00:46:36.840 --> 00:46:40.270
What happens is,
in steady state,

00:46:40.270 --> 00:46:42.270
if everything is
stationary, of course,

00:46:42.270 --> 00:46:44.070
there can't be an exchange.

00:46:44.070 --> 00:46:46.125
But, if you're for
instance, saying--

00:46:46.125 --> 00:46:50.300
and I give you no part of the
solution-- if you have atoms,

00:46:50.300 --> 00:46:54.240
and they are attracted
by the dipole force,

00:46:54.240 --> 00:46:58.260
there's a strong laser beam and
the atoms are accelerated in,

00:46:58.260 --> 00:47:02.450
and you're now asking, where
does the energy come from?

00:47:02.450 --> 00:47:06.110
Because all of what the
atoms do, at least according

00:47:06.110 --> 00:47:09.010
to what I'm telling
you, they redistribute

00:47:09.010 --> 00:47:12.810
photons of energy, h
bar omega, into photons

00:47:12.810 --> 00:47:14.260
of energy, h bar omega.

00:47:14.260 --> 00:47:17.080
So where does the
energy come from?

00:47:17.080 --> 00:47:19.590
You have to go higher in
the approximation here

00:47:19.590 --> 00:47:22.471
to understand where
the energy comes from.

00:47:22.471 --> 00:47:23.970
Let me just tell
you one thing, this

00:47:23.970 --> 00:47:27.690
is actually something which
I've encountered several times.

00:47:27.690 --> 00:47:31.850
And it can be really
confusing, I've

00:47:31.850 --> 00:47:35.130
really proven to mathematically
the this is false.

00:47:35.130 --> 00:47:38.000
So in this level of treatment,
with these very simple

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:41.960
concepts, we correctly
obtained the optical force.

00:47:41.960 --> 00:47:47.880
But if you're now asking,
where does the energy go?

00:47:47.880 --> 00:47:49.920
You have to go deeper.

00:47:49.920 --> 00:47:51.900
And, for instance,
what happens is

00:47:51.900 --> 00:47:54.760
if you take a cloud of
atoms, and the cloud of atoms

00:47:54.760 --> 00:47:57.310
moves in an out
of a laser beam--

00:47:57.310 --> 00:48:01.100
just think of it as
center of mass dipole

00:48:01.100 --> 00:48:06.150
oscillations of a Boson-Einstein
condensate in an optical dipole

00:48:06.150 --> 00:48:10.540
trap-- what happens is when
the atoms move in and out,

00:48:10.540 --> 00:48:14.830
they actually act as a phase
modulator for the laser beam.

00:48:14.830 --> 00:48:18.270
The index of the refraction of
your laser beam is changing.

00:48:18.270 --> 00:48:21.530
So therefore-- and we
don't deal with that

00:48:21.530 --> 00:48:24.170
when he replace the
electromagnetic field by a c

00:48:24.170 --> 00:48:29.940
number-- your laser beam, when
the atoms move in will actually

00:48:29.940 --> 00:48:33.380
show a frequency modulation.

00:48:33.380 --> 00:48:36.440
And you will find-- and it's a
wonderful homework assignment,

00:48:36.440 --> 00:48:38.270
I'm pretty proud
that we created it,

00:48:38.270 --> 00:48:40.020
and that it works
out so easily-- you

00:48:40.020 --> 00:48:42.760
will find that the kinetic
energy of the atoms

00:48:42.760 --> 00:48:45.740
is exactly compensated
by the energy shift

00:48:45.740 --> 00:48:49.550
the photons which have
passed through the atoms.

00:48:49.550 --> 00:48:51.940
But I'm giving you a
very advanced answer.

00:48:51.940 --> 00:48:55.130
It's often very difficult
if you have a simple picture

00:48:55.130 --> 00:48:58.260
for the force to figure out
what happens to the energy.

00:49:01.470 --> 00:49:05.030
Actually, let me give
you the other example.

00:49:05.030 --> 00:49:07.190
When we have the
previous example,

00:49:07.190 --> 00:49:09.990
where we have atoms and
we have a laser beam

00:49:09.990 --> 00:49:13.550
which cools with a
radiation pressure.

00:49:13.550 --> 00:49:26.790
This was our previous example.

00:49:26.790 --> 00:49:28.640
Where does the energy go?

00:49:28.640 --> 00:49:32.150
I have a wonderful correct--
within the assumptions--

00:49:32.150 --> 00:49:34.610
an exact expression
for the force.

00:49:34.610 --> 00:49:35.700
Where does the energy go?

00:49:39.660 --> 00:49:44.530
The atoms have a
counter-propagating laser beam.

00:49:44.530 --> 00:49:49.080
They scatter photons
with this rate.

00:49:49.080 --> 00:49:52.590
Every time they scatter
a photon, they slow down

00:49:52.590 --> 00:49:53.750
by h bar k.

00:49:53.750 --> 00:49:56.430
They lose energy.

00:49:56.430 --> 00:49:58.310
We have a complete
description what

00:49:58.310 --> 00:50:03.189
happens in the momentum
picture and in forces.

00:50:03.189 --> 00:50:04.480
But where does the energy come?

00:50:04.480 --> 00:50:05.646
Or where does the energy go?

00:50:05.646 --> 00:50:07.964
The energy where
the atoms have lost?

00:50:07.964 --> 00:50:10.374
AUDIENCE: They absorb a
slightly high frequency

00:50:10.374 --> 00:50:12.302
with a Doppler shift.

00:50:12.302 --> 00:50:16.158
And then slow down
and then re-release

00:50:16.158 --> 00:50:18.429
a photon with
slightly lower energy.

00:50:18.429 --> 00:50:19.220
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:50:19.220 --> 00:50:21.850
So in that case, it
actually depends which way.

00:50:21.850 --> 00:50:25.160
When the atom loses
energy, the energy

00:50:25.160 --> 00:50:27.760
goes into blue-shifted photons.

00:50:27.760 --> 00:50:30.730
I'm just saying, in order to
address the question, what

00:50:30.730 --> 00:50:34.290
happens to the energy, we have
to bring in our physics, which

00:50:34.290 --> 00:50:37.830
we didn't even consider
to address here.

00:50:37.830 --> 00:50:42.120
It is now the physics of the
spontaneously emitted photons.

00:50:42.120 --> 00:50:45.380
We said for the force,
spontaneous emission vacuum

00:50:45.380 --> 00:50:47.710
fluctuations can be eliminated.

00:50:47.710 --> 00:50:52.530
But if you try to understand
where does the energy go,

00:50:52.530 --> 00:50:55.690
we have to go to those
terms, and we even

00:50:55.690 --> 00:50:59.990
find the physics of Doppler
shifts, which we didn't put in,

00:50:59.990 --> 00:51:01.510
which we didn't
even assume here.

00:51:01.510 --> 00:51:05.630
But, of course, it has
to be self consistent.

00:51:05.630 --> 00:51:10.210
So therefore, you sometimes have
to go to very different physics

00:51:10.210 --> 00:51:12.350
which isn't even
covered by your equation

00:51:12.350 --> 00:51:14.890
to see the flip
side of the coin.

00:51:14.890 --> 00:51:17.710
One side is forces,
which are very simple,

00:51:17.710 --> 00:51:21.740
but the other side of the
coin can be more difficult.

00:51:21.740 --> 00:51:26.790
We'll actually come back to
that when we talk about cooling

00:51:26.790 --> 00:51:28.120
[INAUDIBLE].

00:51:28.120 --> 00:51:31.540
Cooling with a stimulated force.

00:51:31.540 --> 00:51:36.890
