00:53:15.510 --> 00:53:16.010
OK.

00:53:16.010 --> 00:53:22.690
So back to the simple
physics of forces.

00:53:22.690 --> 00:53:24.520
We don't need to
understand the energy,

00:53:24.520 --> 00:53:27.220
because we know the forces,
but we'll come back to that.

00:53:27.220 --> 00:53:30.200
So we have the reactive force.

00:53:30.200 --> 00:53:33.840
The reactive force
is written here.

00:53:33.840 --> 00:53:35.330
What have we done?

00:53:35.330 --> 00:53:38.240
Well, you remember
the alpha vector

00:53:38.240 --> 00:53:41.210
was the gradient of
the Rabi frequency,

00:53:41.210 --> 00:53:45.520
and we have to multiply with the
u component of the steady state

00:53:45.520 --> 00:53:47.840
solution of the
Optical Bloch Equation.

00:53:47.840 --> 00:53:49.540
Here it is, just put together.

00:53:52.600 --> 00:53:54.486
It's a nice expression.

00:53:54.486 --> 00:53:58.340
There are two things you
should know about it.

00:53:58.340 --> 00:54:02.850
The first one is
that you can actually

00:54:02.850 --> 00:54:05.955
write this force exactly as
the gradient of a potential.

00:54:10.670 --> 00:54:13.620
So there is a dipole
potential, and is

00:54:13.620 --> 00:54:15.860
exactly this dipole
potential which

00:54:15.860 --> 00:54:18.920
is used as a trapping potential
when you have dipole traps.

00:54:22.900 --> 00:54:27.700
Probably 99% of you use
dipole traps in the limit

00:54:27.700 --> 00:54:30.050
where the detuning is large.

00:54:30.050 --> 00:54:33.780
And then the logarithm of
1 plus x simply becomes x,

00:54:33.780 --> 00:54:37.050
and you have the simple
expression you are using.

00:54:37.050 --> 00:54:39.410
But in a way, this
is remarkable.

00:54:39.410 --> 00:54:45.220
The dipole force can be
derived from a potential,

00:54:45.220 --> 00:54:48.560
even if the detuning
is small, and you

00:54:48.560 --> 00:54:52.090
have a hell of a lot of
spontaneous scattering, which

00:54:52.090 --> 00:54:57.010
is usually not regarded as being
due to conservative potential.

00:54:57.010 --> 00:54:59.010
So this expression,
that the reactive force

00:54:59.010 --> 00:55:02.760
is a gradient of a potential,
even applies to a situation

00:55:02.760 --> 00:55:07.490
where gamma spontaneous
scattering [INAUDIBLE]

00:55:07.490 --> 00:55:09.610
And you're not
simply in-- and this

00:55:09.610 --> 00:55:12.300
is what this last term is--
in the perturbative limit

00:55:12.300 --> 00:55:15.270
of the AC Stark Effect.

00:55:15.270 --> 00:55:15.770
OK.

00:55:15.770 --> 00:55:18.140
That's number one you should
know about this expression.

00:55:18.140 --> 00:55:25.020
The second thing is if you
look at this expression,

00:55:25.020 --> 00:55:28.640
the question is, what is
the maximum reactive force?

00:55:28.640 --> 00:55:33.770
We talked about the maximum
spontaneous, or dissipative

00:55:33.770 --> 00:55:37.110
force, which is h
bar k, the momentum

00:55:37.110 --> 00:55:40.190
of a photon times gamms over 2.

00:55:40.190 --> 00:55:43.090
What is the maximum
force you can get out

00:55:43.090 --> 00:55:45.750
of the reactive force?

00:55:45.750 --> 00:55:48.600
Well, of course, if you
want a lot of force,

00:55:48.600 --> 00:55:50.660
you want to use a
lot of laser power.

00:55:50.660 --> 00:55:54.750
Therefore, you want to
use a high Rabi frequency.

00:55:54.750 --> 00:55:58.010
And now, if you want to use
your laser power wisely,

00:55:58.010 --> 00:56:01.500
the question is, how should
you pick the detuning?

00:56:01.500 --> 00:56:04.425
And you realize if you
pick the detuning small,

00:56:04.425 --> 00:56:07.370
there is a prefector
which goes to zero,

00:56:07.370 --> 00:56:09.815
but if you pick your
detuning extremely large,

00:56:09.815 --> 00:56:12.410
the denominator kills you.

00:56:12.410 --> 00:56:17.200
And well, if you analyze it
and or stare at this expression

00:56:17.200 --> 00:56:19.390
for more than a
second, you realize

00:56:19.390 --> 00:56:23.710
that the optimum detuning
is when the detuning is

00:56:23.710 --> 00:56:26.810
on the order of
the Rabi frequency.

00:56:26.810 --> 00:56:30.980
And if you plug
that in, you find

00:56:30.980 --> 00:56:33.420
that under those
optimum conditions,

00:56:33.420 --> 00:56:37.720
the reactive force
can be written again

00:56:37.720 --> 00:56:41.150
as the momentum of
a photon-- it must

00:56:41.150 --> 00:56:45.480
be, the momentum of the
photon is the unit of force,

00:56:45.480 --> 00:56:47.650
the quantum of force,
which has to appear--

00:56:47.650 --> 00:56:50.500
but not the frequency
is not gamma,

00:56:50.500 --> 00:56:55.940
but it is the Rabi frequency.

00:56:55.940 --> 00:56:58.300
So the picture you
should sort of have

00:56:58.300 --> 00:57:00.880
is that under those
situations, just

00:57:00.880 --> 00:57:03.530
assume the standing wave
consists of two traveling

00:57:03.530 --> 00:57:06.160
waves, and the atom
is Rabi flopping.

00:57:06.160 --> 00:57:09.690
But it is Rabi flopping
in a way that it goes up

00:57:09.690 --> 00:57:12.680
by taking a photon
from one laser beam,

00:57:12.680 --> 00:57:15.520
and then it goes down
by emitting the photon

00:57:15.520 --> 00:57:17.080
into the other laser beam.

00:57:17.080 --> 00:57:21.210
So during each
Rabi flux cycle, it

00:57:21.210 --> 00:57:24.650
exchanges a momentum
of 2 h bar k

00:57:24.650 --> 00:57:28.030
with the electromagnetic field.

00:57:28.030 --> 00:57:32.270
So therefore, the reactive
force-- the stimulated force--

00:57:32.270 --> 00:57:38.690
never saturates if you increase
the Rabi frequency-- depending,

00:57:38.690 --> 00:57:41.220
of course, on your detuning,
but if you choose the detuning

00:57:41.220 --> 00:57:43.630
correctly-- you can
get a force which

00:57:43.630 --> 00:57:45.530
is just going
further and further.

