So the atom is first taking
care of its momentum--

01:03:44.830 --> 01:03:47.680
is losing momentum--
by stimulated force,

01:03:47.680 --> 01:03:50.250
and eventually,
before it's too late,

01:03:50.250 --> 01:03:52.590
it has to do some
spontaneous emission where

01:03:52.590 --> 01:03:57.250
it is paying back it debts
in energy to Heisenberg.

01:03:57.250 --> 01:04:02.210
So and of course, after a
certain time, everything is OK.

01:04:02.210 --> 01:04:04.900
The force was provided
by exchanging photons

01:04:04.900 --> 01:04:06.400
of identical frequency.

01:04:06.400 --> 01:04:10.410
And the energy is provided by an
occasional spontaneous emission

01:04:10.410 --> 01:04:13.870
event, using one
of the [INAUDIBLE].

01:04:13.870 --> 01:04:16.010
So everything is there.

01:04:16.010 --> 01:04:18.970
Everything is a perfect
picture, but you

01:04:18.970 --> 01:04:21.610
have to sort of, in
this description,

01:04:21.610 --> 01:04:24.770
allow a certain uncertainty
that the force is

01:04:24.770 --> 01:04:27.420
the exchange of
identical photons,

01:04:27.420 --> 01:04:30.330
and the energy
balance is reconciled

01:04:30.330 --> 01:04:32.550
in spontaneous emission.

01:04:32.550 --> 01:04:39.110
And on any longer time scale
there are enough events

01:04:39.110 --> 01:04:42.040
that the balance is
perfectly matched.

01:04:42.040 --> 01:04:43.950
But if you would
take the position,

01:04:43.950 --> 01:04:45.440
no, this is not possible.

01:04:45.440 --> 01:04:50.830
You know, the atom can only-- I
mean, it's sort of in diagrams.

01:04:50.830 --> 01:04:54.290
It's not that one diagram
which scatters a photon

01:04:54.290 --> 01:04:55.910
has to conserve energy.

01:04:55.910 --> 01:04:57.160
You have a little bit of time.

01:04:57.160 --> 01:04:59.630
You have Heisenberg's
uncertainty time

01:04:59.630 --> 01:05:02.510
to make sure that
another diagram jumps

01:05:02.510 --> 01:05:06.560
in, and reconciles
energy conservation.

01:05:06.560 --> 01:05:08.740
That's at least my way
of looking into it,

01:05:08.740 --> 01:05:11.750
but it's a very maybe, my
personal interpretation

01:05:11.750 --> 01:05:15.120
of how all these diagrams
and photon scattering

01:05:15.120 --> 01:05:16.670
events work together.

01:05:21.100 --> 01:05:21.600
OK.

01:05:21.600 --> 01:05:24.300
Let's do something simpler now.

01:05:24.300 --> 01:05:29.220
So I've explained to you
the dissipative force,

01:05:29.220 --> 01:05:36.290
the reactive force,
and in the next unit

01:05:36.290 --> 01:05:40.100
I want to show you
simply applications

01:05:40.100 --> 01:05:41.890
of the spontaneous force.

01:05:41.890 --> 01:05:44.500
In every experiment
on cold atoms,

01:05:44.500 --> 01:05:47.530
the spontaneous force
is center stage.

01:05:47.530 --> 01:05:50.990
It is necessary to
slow down atomic beams.

01:05:50.990 --> 01:05:55.610
It provides molasses, which
is the colling of atoms

01:05:55.610 --> 01:06:00.230
to micro-Kelvin temperature,
and the spontaneous force

01:06:00.230 --> 01:06:03.460
is also responsible for
the Magneto-optical trap.

01:06:03.460 --> 01:06:06.830
So what I want to
do here is, again,

01:06:06.830 --> 01:06:13.210
by showing you the
relevant equations, how

01:06:13.210 --> 01:06:16.040
the spontaneous force, which
we have just discussed,

01:06:16.040 --> 01:06:18.830
how these spontaneous
force leads to those three

01:06:18.830 --> 01:06:21.340
applications.

01:06:21.340 --> 01:06:24.200
So this is one of the
most experimental sections

01:06:24.200 --> 01:06:27.740
of this course, because this
equation has it all in it.

01:06:27.740 --> 01:06:31.700
And I just want to show you how
this equation can be applied

01:06:31.700 --> 01:06:35.180
to three different important
experimental geometries.

01:06:45.450 --> 01:06:47.770
OK.

01:06:47.770 --> 01:06:51.500
So this is our equation.

01:06:51.500 --> 01:06:55.210
It has the momentum
transfer per photon.

01:06:55.210 --> 01:06:58.430
It has the maximum scatter
rate, gamma over two.

01:06:58.430 --> 01:07:05.930
And then, here, it has
the Lorentzian line shape.

01:07:05.930 --> 01:07:11.050
And the important thing is
when we talk about molasses

01:07:11.050 --> 01:07:14.910
and beam slowing is that
the detuning is the laser

01:07:14.910 --> 01:07:17.270
detuning and the
Doppler detuning.

01:07:17.270 --> 01:07:20.850
So the velocity
dependence enters now

01:07:20.850 --> 01:07:24.780
the spontaneous force through
the detuning in the Lorentzian

01:07:24.780 --> 01:07:28.910
denominator, and it enters
through the Doppler effect.

01:07:28.910 --> 01:07:30.750
So you can pretty
much say it like this,

01:07:30.750 --> 01:07:32.360
if you have a bunch
of laser beam,

01:07:32.360 --> 01:07:36.760
and slow and cool your atoms,
how can the lasers do the job?

01:07:36.760 --> 01:07:39.640
Well, they measure the
velocity of the atoms

01:07:39.640 --> 01:07:41.100
through the Doppler shift.

01:07:41.100 --> 01:07:43.240
And if is the Doppler
shift which tells

01:07:43.240 --> 01:07:45.181
the laser beams what
to do, so to speak.

01:07:45.181 --> 01:07:46.680
And this is how
laser cooling works.

01:07:50.050 --> 01:07:52.590
So just as an
experimentalist, you

01:07:52.590 --> 01:07:55.790
should actually know
what the scale is.

01:08:00.930 --> 01:08:02.740
If somebody asked
you, how strong

01:08:02.740 --> 01:08:05.620
is the spontaneous
scattering force?

01:08:05.620 --> 01:08:08.170
Well, a way to connect
it with real time

01:08:08.170 --> 01:08:10.880
units-- with real
life units-- is,

01:08:10.880 --> 01:08:13.400
what is the maximum
deceleration?

01:08:13.400 --> 01:08:17.740
Well, this is 10 to
the 5 G. You can ask,

01:08:17.740 --> 01:08:19.470
is 10 to the 5 G a lot?

01:08:19.470 --> 01:08:20.660
Or not?

01:08:20.660 --> 01:08:23.520
Well, for an astronaut,
it would be a lot.

01:08:23.520 --> 01:08:24.620
It would.

01:08:24.620 --> 01:08:28.870
No living organism can
sustain 10 to the 5 G.

01:08:28.870 --> 01:08:33.109
But I'm really surprised
when I did this calculation.

01:08:33.109 --> 01:08:36.510
When you compare it
to the electric force

01:08:36.510 --> 01:08:40.540
on an ionized atom,
the same force,

01:08:40.540 --> 01:08:43.540
which is provided by the
spontaneous light force,

01:08:43.540 --> 01:08:46.040
would be provided
by an electric field

01:08:46.040 --> 01:08:49.050
of one millivolt per centimeter.

01:08:49.050 --> 01:08:51.235
So it's not easy if you
have a stainless steel

01:08:51.235 --> 01:08:53.359
chamber to avoid
petch effects, which

01:08:53.359 --> 01:08:55.359
create those electric fields.

01:08:55.359 --> 01:08:57.109
And if you've a
battery with 9 volt,

01:08:57.109 --> 01:09:00.120
a centimeter apart--
just a 9 volt battery--

01:09:00.120 --> 01:09:03.950
would accelerate an ion
four orders of magnitude

01:09:03.950 --> 01:09:10.819
faster than your beloved
strong spontaneous light force.

01:09:10.819 --> 01:09:13.720
So in that sense,
10 to the 5 G is

01:09:13.720 --> 01:09:16.210
a lot in the macroscopic
world, but if you

01:09:16.210 --> 01:09:18.950
would look at microscopic
forces-- which are often

01:09:18.950 --> 01:09:21.750
electric forces--
it's absolutely tiny.

01:09:21.750 --> 01:09:24.140
And sometimes I say,
the fact that you

01:09:24.140 --> 01:09:31.580
can do 100 kilovolt
per centimeter,

01:09:31.580 --> 01:09:33.840
that you can make
electric forces which

01:09:33.840 --> 01:09:36.439
are seven, eight, or
nine, orders of magnitude

01:09:36.439 --> 01:09:41.050
stronger, that's actually
the reason why ion traps were

01:09:41.050 --> 01:09:44.950
invented before trapping
of neutral particles.

01:09:44.950 --> 01:09:47.809
So some developments
in the field

01:09:47.809 --> 01:09:49.970
of trapping particles--
and eventually

01:09:49.970 --> 01:09:53.569
laser cooling them-- it
first started with ion traps,

01:09:53.569 --> 01:09:56.290
and then it proceeded
to neutral atoms.

01:09:56.290 --> 01:09:58.255
And the reason is
the ion trappers

01:09:58.255 --> 01:10:00.892
have forces at
their disposal which

01:10:00.892 --> 01:10:02.850
are eight or nine orders
of magnitude stronger.

01:10:06.920 --> 01:10:09.070
OK.

01:10:09.070 --> 01:10:09.835
Optical molasses.

01:10:13.790 --> 01:10:17.340
I know some of you will
hate it, because I've just

01:10:17.340 --> 01:10:23.080
explained to you that
in a standing wave,

01:10:23.080 --> 01:10:25.250
we don't have any
spontaneous light force,

01:10:25.250 --> 01:10:29.120
all we have is the reactive
force, the stimulated force,

01:10:29.120 --> 01:10:31.250
because it is the
u, the in phase

01:10:31.250 --> 01:10:35.120
oscillation of the atomic
dipole operator which

01:10:35.120 --> 01:10:38.170
is responsible for everything.

01:10:38.170 --> 01:10:40.940
But now I'm just, you
know, wearing another hat,

01:10:40.940 --> 01:10:47.420
and I tell you that there is a
limit where the total force can

01:10:47.420 --> 01:10:50.810
be regarded with some
of the two forces.

01:10:50.810 --> 01:10:54.940
So therefore, I'm
pretending now that if you

01:10:54.940 --> 01:10:59.040
have near resonant light
in a standing wave,

01:10:59.040 --> 01:11:02.670
that the force in the
standing wave-- which you know

01:11:02.670 --> 01:11:06.080
is a purely reactive
force-- can now

01:11:06.080 --> 01:11:10.400
be written as the sum of
the two propagating waves.

01:11:10.400 --> 01:11:12.580
And, of course, each
propagating wave

01:11:12.580 --> 01:11:17.330
does a purely dissipative force.

01:11:17.330 --> 01:11:19.900
That is, what I'm telling you
can be mathematically proven.

01:11:22.670 --> 01:11:28.410
That the stimulated force
in a standing wave is equal

01:11:28.410 --> 01:11:32.420
to the sum of the two
dissipative forces or each

01:11:32.420 --> 01:11:34.870
travelling wave.

01:11:34.870 --> 01:11:37.470
I just keep that
in mind whenever

01:11:37.470 --> 01:11:40.690
you think you can
rigorously distinguish

01:11:40.690 --> 01:11:44.340
between the dissipative force
and the stimulated force.

01:11:44.340 --> 01:11:47.090
Keep in mind that
a standing wave--

01:11:47.090 --> 01:11:49.490
which has only a
stimulated force,

01:11:49.490 --> 01:11:55.740
as I rigorously proved to you--
can alternatively be described

01:11:55.740 --> 01:11:58.730
as the sum of two
spontaneous light forces,

01:11:58.730 --> 01:12:00.980
each of which provided by
one of the travelling waves.

01:12:04.250 --> 01:12:07.550
Well, it sort of makes sense
in a perturbative limit.

01:12:07.550 --> 01:12:10.069
You can just take one beam,
you can take the other beam,

01:12:10.069 --> 01:12:11.985
and the combined effect
of the two laser beams

01:12:11.985 --> 01:12:12.990
is higher order.

01:12:12.990 --> 01:12:16.817
So the fact that in
some low intensity limit

01:12:16.817 --> 01:12:18.400
this has to be valid,
is pretty clear.

01:12:23.450 --> 01:12:29.220
Anyway, but just a
warning, if you really

01:12:29.220 --> 01:12:32.100
want to use a stimulated force
here, you're in big trouble.

01:12:32.100 --> 01:12:34.470
It's much, much harder
to get this result out

01:12:34.470 --> 01:12:35.860
of the stimulated force.

01:12:35.860 --> 01:12:39.720
Because to get a stimulated
force with velocity dependence

01:12:39.720 --> 01:12:43.270
requires you to take
solutions of the Optical Bloch

01:12:43.270 --> 01:12:46.980
Equations, which are not steady
state, but non-adiabatic.

01:12:46.980 --> 01:12:47.990
So just a warning.

01:12:47.990 --> 01:12:50.900
You can do it, if you want
with a stimulated force,

01:12:50.900 --> 01:12:53.900
but I would strongly
advise you to first use

01:12:53.900 --> 01:12:56.760
the simpler formalism.

01:12:56.760 --> 01:12:59.750
You have to go to very different
approximation schemes and much

01:12:59.750 --> 01:13:01.700
more technical
complexity if you want

01:13:01.700 --> 01:13:04.630
to get it out of the
stimulated force.

01:13:04.630 --> 01:13:05.250
OK.

01:13:05.250 --> 01:13:09.310
So with that assumption,
you'll remember

01:13:09.310 --> 01:13:13.310
we had the dissipative
force of each laser beam.

01:13:13.310 --> 01:13:15.270
Now we have two laser beams.

01:13:15.270 --> 01:13:16.460
We summed them up.

01:13:16.460 --> 01:13:19.400
Because the two laser beams
come from different directions,

01:13:19.400 --> 01:13:20.940
we have a minus sign here.

01:13:20.940 --> 01:13:24.040
And for the same reason,
we have plus and minus sign

01:13:24.040 --> 01:13:26.350
in the Doppler effect.

01:13:26.350 --> 01:13:29.240
So what we have
is the following,

01:13:29.240 --> 01:13:34.205
each force of each laser beam
has this Lorentzian envelope,

01:13:34.205 --> 01:13:39.010
shown in black, but the other
force of the other laser beam

01:13:39.010 --> 01:13:40.400
has the opposite sign.

01:13:40.400 --> 01:13:43.980
And the two have
opposite Doppler shifts.

01:13:43.980 --> 01:13:49.410
So if I add up the two black
forces, I get the red force.

01:13:49.410 --> 01:13:53.180
And the red force is
anti-symmetric with respect

01:13:53.180 --> 01:13:54.540
to velocity.

01:13:54.540 --> 01:13:58.350
So therefore, in the
limit of small velocities

01:13:58.350 --> 01:14:02.100
I get a force which is
minus alpha times v.

01:14:02.100 --> 01:14:06.120
And this is the
force of friction.

01:14:06.120 --> 01:14:09.580
And in a whimsical way,
people called this arrangement

01:14:09.580 --> 01:14:13.690
of two traveling
waves Optical Molasses

01:14:13.690 --> 01:14:18.820
because the atom
literally gets stuck

01:14:18.820 --> 01:14:21.550
in this configuration
like a tiny ball

01:14:21.550 --> 01:14:24.060
bearing you throw into honey.

01:14:24.060 --> 01:14:27.340
So this is optical molasses.

01:14:27.340 --> 01:14:29.980
Actually, I think
some of the Europeans

01:14:29.980 --> 01:14:32.790
had to learn the
word molasses for it.

01:14:32.790 --> 01:14:35.110
In the US, everybody
knows what molasses is.

01:14:35.110 --> 01:14:37.200
Well, in Europe, we
know what honey is,

01:14:37.200 --> 01:14:39.490
but molasses is not
a standard staple.

01:14:39.490 --> 01:14:43.210
But anyway, it's
optical molasses.

01:14:43.210 --> 01:14:44.840
OK.

01:14:44.840 --> 01:14:46.220
Very simple result.

01:14:46.220 --> 01:14:50.390
And, again, it's not easy to get
it out of the stimulated force.

01:14:50.390 --> 01:14:52.990
But it's possible.

01:14:52.990 --> 01:14:55.390
I will actually tell you
how we get cooling out

01:14:55.390 --> 01:14:57.659
of the stimulated force
later in some limit.

01:14:57.659 --> 01:15:00.154
AUDIENCE: Is there
[INAUDIBLE] why

01:15:00.154 --> 01:15:05.643
this assumption of dissipative
forces is easier [INAUDIBLE]

01:15:05.643 --> 01:15:08.637
and the stimulated force will
be made difficult [INAUDIBLE]?

01:15:20.792 --> 01:15:22.250
PROFESSOR: I'm not
sure if there is

01:15:22.250 --> 01:15:25.010
a simple answer why it's easier.

01:15:25.010 --> 01:15:26.880
Well, it can't be
easier than that.

01:15:32.875 --> 01:15:35.125
AUDIENCE: I mean, there has
to be something wrong with

01:15:35.125 --> 01:15:38.990
our assumptions of stimulated
forces so that we cannot get

01:15:38.990 --> 01:15:39.490
[INAUDIBLE]

01:15:39.490 --> 01:15:40.156
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:15:40.156 --> 01:15:42.880
I think what happens
is what I briefly said.

01:15:42.880 --> 01:15:45.700
To the best of my knowledge,
but I'm not 100% certain.

01:15:45.700 --> 01:15:48.060
We have the simply
expression because we

01:15:48.060 --> 01:15:52.000
have used the steady state
solution of the Optical Bloch

01:15:52.000 --> 01:15:52.640
Equation.

01:15:52.640 --> 01:15:54.460
In other words, we
have a laser beam,

01:15:54.460 --> 01:15:57.650
and it's just the power of
the laser which tells us

01:15:57.650 --> 01:15:59.080
how much light
scattering happens.

01:15:59.080 --> 01:16:01.020
And we use the steady
state solution.

01:16:01.020 --> 01:16:04.200
And we sort of have folded that
into the force for one laser

01:16:04.200 --> 01:16:04.720
beam.

01:16:04.720 --> 01:16:06.094
And then we have
the same package

01:16:06.094 --> 01:16:07.500
for the other laser beam.

01:16:07.500 --> 01:16:10.100
And we have never considered
that the two laser

01:16:10.100 --> 01:16:11.870
beam may have some cross talk.

01:16:11.870 --> 01:16:15.810
And this is indeed valid
for all low laser power.

01:16:15.810 --> 01:16:18.080
However, if you want
to get cooling out

01:16:18.080 --> 01:16:23.270
off the stimulated force, I
will show some of you later,

01:16:23.270 --> 01:16:26.100
you can no longer use
the steady state solution

01:16:26.100 --> 01:16:29.790
because it would
miss the effect here.

01:16:29.790 --> 01:16:32.360
You wouldn't get any
cooling out of it.

01:16:32.360 --> 01:16:34.990
In order to get something
which is dissipative,

01:16:34.990 --> 01:16:36.670
out of a reactive
force-- reactive

01:16:36.670 --> 01:16:38.830
force is by definition
not dissipative--

01:16:38.830 --> 01:16:40.820
you need a
dissipation mechanism.

01:16:40.820 --> 01:16:43.950
And the dissipation
mechanism is that you're not

01:16:43.950 --> 01:16:48.150
quite steady state, there is
a relaxation time, a time lag.

01:16:48.150 --> 01:16:51.870
The atom is not instantaneously
in its steady state solution.

01:16:51.870 --> 01:16:54.200
It needs a little bit
of time to adjust.

01:16:54.200 --> 01:17:00.440
And it is these time lag of
the atom which eventually gives

01:17:00.440 --> 01:17:02.920
rise to an alpha coefficient
in the stimulated force.

01:17:02.920 --> 01:17:04.808
AUDIENCE: So then
physically, you are,

01:17:04.808 --> 01:17:07.168
during cooling experiments,
you can take care

01:17:07.168 --> 01:17:09.370
that you are actually not
in the steady state limit?

01:17:15.010 --> 01:17:18.500
PROFESSOR: What I'm telling you
is, for the spontaneous force,

01:17:18.500 --> 01:17:22.180
we get in leading order
the effect by assuming

01:17:22.180 --> 01:17:25.210
the steady state limit, but
if you want to get it out

01:17:25.210 --> 01:17:27.735
of the stimulated
force, as far as I know,

01:17:27.735 --> 01:17:29.875
you don't get it with
the steady state limit.

01:17:29.875 --> 01:17:30.416
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:17:34.520 --> 01:17:36.830
PROFESSOR: If you use
different approaches--

01:17:36.830 --> 01:17:39.500
I mean this is why you
want to pick your approach.

01:17:39.500 --> 01:17:42.570
Sometimes you get something
already in lower order.

01:17:42.570 --> 01:17:44.760
Sometimes you get
it in higher order.

01:17:44.760 --> 01:17:47.060
And I think one
favorite example is

01:17:47.060 --> 01:17:50.300
you solve this problem
about [INAUDIBLE] scattering

01:17:50.300 --> 01:17:53.380
and Thompson scattering, pick
your Hamiltonian, d dot e,

01:17:53.380 --> 01:17:55.650
or p minus a.

01:17:55.650 --> 01:17:58.221
In one case, you have to work
harder than in the other case.

01:17:58.221 --> 01:17:59.470
And I think here it's similar.

01:18:02.790 --> 01:18:09.680
Anyway, let's just put
in-- I think that's, yeah,

01:18:09.680 --> 01:18:12.130
we can do in the
next few minutes.

01:18:12.130 --> 01:18:18.190
So we now want to
put in the effect

01:18:18.190 --> 01:18:20.070
that the force fluctuates.

01:18:20.070 --> 01:18:23.170
And that means we have heating.

01:18:23.170 --> 01:18:27.840
Before I do that, let me just
tell you what the solution is

01:18:27.840 --> 01:18:32.320
for force equals minus
alpha times v. Well,

01:18:32.320 --> 01:18:35.890
it means we extract
energy out of the system

01:18:35.890 --> 01:18:39.150
at a rate-- Well,
energy per unit time

01:18:39.150 --> 01:18:42.490
is force times velocity.

01:18:42.490 --> 01:18:46.355
Force times velocity is now
minus alpha times v square.

01:18:46.355 --> 01:18:49.760
But v square is the
energy, the kinetic energy.

01:18:49.760 --> 01:18:53.110
In other words, this
equation tells us

01:18:53.110 --> 01:18:59.030
that the atomic motion,
the kinetic energy,

01:18:59.030 --> 01:19:04.310
is exponentially [? damned. ?]
And if there were nothing else,

01:19:04.310 --> 01:19:07.510
you just need two laser
beams-- optical molasses--

01:19:07.510 --> 01:19:10.980
and you would go not just to
micro-Kelvin, but to nano-

01:19:10.980 --> 01:19:12.750
and pico- Kelvin temperatures.

01:19:12.750 --> 01:19:16.910
It's an exponential
decay to absolute zero.

01:19:16.910 --> 01:19:19.440
However, we don't
each reach nano-

01:19:19.440 --> 01:19:22.389
and pico- Kelvin
temperatures in laser cooling

01:19:22.389 --> 01:19:23.805
because there are
other processes.

01:19:27.450 --> 01:19:30.900
And what is important here
is spontaneous emission.

01:19:35.560 --> 01:19:36.520
OK.

01:19:36.520 --> 01:19:39.460
So the way you treat
spontaneous emission is

01:19:39.460 --> 01:19:44.770
the following, every time an
atom emits spontaneously, there

01:19:44.770 --> 01:19:49.740
is a random momentum
kick of h bar k.

01:19:49.740 --> 01:19:54.900
If you have n photons scattered
because the momentum kicks

01:19:54.900 --> 01:19:58.140
going random direction, they
only add up in a random box.

01:19:58.140 --> 01:20:01.280
You get square root
N. Or if you ask,

01:20:01.280 --> 01:20:06.700
what is the average of p square
due to spontaneously emission?

01:20:06.700 --> 01:20:09.500
It is the momentum
of the photon squared

01:20:09.500 --> 01:20:12.310
times the number of
scattering events.

01:20:12.310 --> 01:20:15.340
So therefore, in the form
of a differential equation,

01:20:15.340 --> 01:20:18.200
the heating rate, or the
derivative of-- the TEMPO

01:20:18.200 --> 01:20:20.770
derivative-- of
p square goes now

01:20:20.770 --> 01:20:22.530
with the number of
photons per unit

01:20:22.530 --> 01:20:23.990
time, which is the
scattering rate.

01:20:27.590 --> 01:20:29.286
OK.

01:20:29.286 --> 01:20:34.870
If you would stop
here, and that's

01:20:34.870 --> 01:20:43.190
what many people do who explain
heating in this situation,

01:20:43.190 --> 01:20:45.510
you would miss half
of the heating,

01:20:45.510 --> 01:20:48.850
because what you
have treated here

01:20:48.850 --> 01:20:52.950
is only the photon transfer
and spontaneous emission.

01:20:52.950 --> 01:20:57.150
However, there is also
fluctuation and absorption.

01:20:57.150 --> 01:21:00.860
I mean just look at two
atoms in the [INAUDIBLE].

01:21:00.860 --> 01:21:03.070
Kind of me and another atom.

01:21:03.070 --> 01:21:05.200
And we both scatter photons.

01:21:05.200 --> 01:21:09.620
On average, in the same laser
beam, we absorb in photons

01:21:09.620 --> 01:21:11.670
and get in momentum kicks.

01:21:11.670 --> 01:21:13.732
But there is
Poissonian statistics

01:21:13.732 --> 01:21:16.620
how many photons I
absorb, and how many

01:21:16.620 --> 01:21:19.100
photons my twin brother absorbs.

01:21:19.100 --> 01:21:22.500
So therefore, due to the
randomness in absorption,

01:21:22.500 --> 01:21:25.010
or the fluctuations
in absorption.

01:21:25.010 --> 01:21:28.550
There is another
square root n variance

01:21:28.550 --> 01:21:34.120
in the recoil kicks which comes
from the absorption process.

01:21:34.120 --> 01:21:37.600
And it so happens, for
exactly that reason,

01:21:37.600 --> 01:21:41.630
that the heating-- the
derivative of kinetic energy,

01:21:41.630 --> 01:21:45.010
or the difference of momentum
squared due to absorption

01:21:45.010 --> 01:21:46.515
is exactly the same
as in emission.

01:21:49.880 --> 01:21:52.100
Well, if you now make
different assumptions,

01:21:52.100 --> 01:21:54.830
spontaneous emission
has a dipole pattern.

01:21:54.830 --> 01:22:01.790
And you can sort of factor on
the order of unity, depending

01:22:01.790 --> 01:22:03.870
what the pattern of the
spontaneous emission

01:22:03.870 --> 01:22:08.540
is, whether you make a 1D or 2D
model of spontaneous emission

01:22:08.540 --> 01:22:11.180
that the photons can only
go in one dimension, in two

01:22:11.180 --> 01:22:12.480
dimension, or three dimensions.

01:22:12.480 --> 01:22:15.170
So you have to get
other prefectors,

01:22:15.170 --> 01:22:19.680
but the picture is that without
going into numerical factors

01:22:19.680 --> 01:22:24.820
on the order of unity, you have
fluctuations in the absorption,

01:22:24.820 --> 01:22:27.090
you have a randomness
in spontaneous emission,

01:22:27.090 --> 01:22:30.760
and they both
equally contribute.

01:22:30.760 --> 01:22:42.300
So that means now the following,
that we have heating rate.

01:22:42.300 --> 01:22:46.730
The heating rate we
just talked about.

01:22:46.730 --> 01:22:48.580
The increase in p square.

01:22:48.580 --> 01:22:51.060
Well, if you divide
by 2 times the mass,

01:22:51.060 --> 01:22:53.790
it's increasing kinetic energy.

01:22:53.790 --> 01:22:56.060
So the increase
in kinetic energy

01:22:56.060 --> 01:22:57.325
is given by this expression.

01:23:00.140 --> 01:23:04.130
And it is common if you
have a heating process

01:23:04.130 --> 01:23:06.290
to introduce a
momentum diffusion

01:23:06.290 --> 01:23:07.680
coefficient in that way.

01:23:07.680 --> 01:23:09.310
It's just the definition.

01:23:09.310 --> 01:23:14.150
It shows you how p square
increases per unit time.

01:23:14.150 --> 01:23:18.320
And now we can get the cooling
limit for spontaneous emission,

01:23:18.320 --> 01:23:21.890
namely by saying,
in steady state when

01:23:21.890 --> 01:23:24.470
we have-- due to
photon scattering--

01:23:24.470 --> 01:23:27.400
the same amount of heating and
the same amount of cooling,

01:23:27.400 --> 01:23:29.530
the temperature will have
asymptotically reached

01:23:29.530 --> 01:23:30.890
a steady state value.

01:23:33.760 --> 01:23:36.890
The heating rate
was parametrized

01:23:36.890 --> 01:23:40.970
by momentum diffusion
coefficient, d over m.

01:23:40.970 --> 01:23:45.090
So this is sort of independent
of the velocity of the atom.

01:23:45.090 --> 01:23:47.670
Whereas you'll remember
the cooling rate

01:23:47.670 --> 01:23:51.000
was proportional to
the energy because it

01:23:51.000 --> 01:23:56.810
was an exponential
approach to zero energy.

01:23:56.810 --> 01:24:00.770
So therefore, when we have the
heating equals the cooling,

01:24:00.770 --> 01:24:03.340
we have the energy
of the atoms there,

01:24:03.340 --> 01:24:06.280
and therefore, we
find that the energy

01:24:06.280 --> 01:24:11.110
of the atoms in steady
state is given by, actually,

01:24:11.110 --> 01:24:15.260
the ratio of heating
versus cooling.

01:24:15.260 --> 01:24:17.120
It's a simple expression.

01:24:17.120 --> 01:24:22.045
The energy or the limiting
temperature for molasses

01:24:22.045 --> 01:24:24.850
is the ratio of
heating versus cooling.

01:24:24.850 --> 01:24:28.800
Heating is described by momentum
diffusion coefficient and alpha

01:24:28.800 --> 01:24:32.330
is described by
the damping force.

01:24:32.330 --> 01:24:35.080
I want you, actually, to
keep this expression in mind.

01:24:35.080 --> 01:24:37.520
A limit in temperature
in laser cooling

01:24:37.520 --> 01:24:40.690
is always-- actually, in other
processes in laser cooling--

01:24:40.690 --> 01:24:43.720
is the ratio of
heating over cooling.

01:24:43.720 --> 01:24:47.550
And momentum diffusion
coefficient due to heating,

01:24:47.550 --> 01:24:50.430
over a friction
force due to cooling.

01:24:50.430 --> 01:24:55.010
Because we will later find
polarization gradient cooling,

01:24:55.010 --> 01:24:56.460
cooling in blue
